SWPM (stochastically weighted particle method) examples and tests
==================================================================

The stochastic weighted particle method gives every simulation particle its
own statistical weight (stored in the custom per-particle attribute
"stochastic_wt" registered by fix stochastic_weight, relative to the global
fnum).  Collisions between particles of unequal weight split off new
particles so the collision itself is always performed between equal-weight
partners; particle reduction merges groups of particles back into a few
moment-preserving survivors to keep the particle count bounded.

Relevant commands (see the doc pages for details):
  fix ID stochastic_weight
  collide_modify stochastic_weight yes
  collide_modify split Ncmin wtf
  collide_modify reduce {energy|heat|stress} {binary|weight} Ncmax Ngmin Ngmax
  compute ID vmom/grid group mix {v2|vx3|vy3|vz3|v4} ...

Example / regression inputs
---------------------------

All inputs run in a few seconds on one processor.  The gold-log regression
tests (suite "swpm", gold logs log.<date>.mpi_<n>.<name>) are KEPT
DETERMINISTIC on purpose: do not change the seeds or parameters without
re-blessing the gold logs.  Single-cell decks pin the full stats trajectory;
the multi-cell deck pins only conserved invariants (so it is reproducible
regardless of MPI rank count / particle ordering).

Gold-log regression tests (single grid cell, full trajectory pinned):
  in.swpm.periodic      homogeneous relaxation, thresholds chosen so neither
                        splitting nor reduction triggers (reduces to plain
                        DSMC with unit weights)
  in.swpm.split         always-split regime (Ncmin > np): np grows while the
                        weighted temperature/density/velocity stay constant
  in.swpm.reduce.energy energy-scheme reduction, binary-tree grouping
  in.swpm.reduce.heat   heat-scheme reduction, binary-tree grouping
  in.swpm.reduce.stress stress-scheme reduction, binary-tree grouping
  in.swpm.vmom          compute vmom/grid velocity moments under SWPM
  in.swpm.boundary      weighted boundary tallies (nflux/press/etot) at
                        diffuse walls of unequal temperature

Gold-log regression test (multi-cell, conserved invariants pinned):
  in.swpm.group.weight  heat-scheme reduction with weight-based grouping on a
                        4x4x1 grid; regression-tests the multi-cell weight
                        grouping (which used to corrupt memory) and pins the
                        conserved global temperature and weighted density

Demonstration examples (not in the gold-log suite):
  in.swpm.1D            1D heat conduction between diffuse walls of unequal
                        temperature; multi-cell SWPM + weighted surface/
                        boundary tallies (trajectory-dependent, so covered
                        deterministically by in.swpm.boundary instead)
  in.swpm.bkw           Bobylev-Krook-Wu relaxation benchmark; requires a
                        particle file generated by bkw_init.py first (see the
                        header of in.swpm.bkw)

MPI determinism: the multi-cell decks set "global comm/sort yes", the SPARTA
idiom for making the particle trajectory reproducible across MPI rank counts.
The single-cell decks need no such option (no particle migration between
cells).  Conserved invariants (temperature, weighted density, momentum) are
independent of particle ordering and reproduce on any rank count either way.

Conservation invariants
-----------------------

Splitting, elastic collisions and all three reduction schemes conserve, per
grid cell and exactly (to floating point roundoff):
  - total particle weight            (=> weighted number density nrho)
  - weighted momentum                (=> weighted mean velocity u,v,w)
  - weighted total energy            (=> weighted temperature)
  - weighted rotational energy
The regression decks print these as stats columns, so any regression that
breaks conservation shows up as a changed column, not just a changed
trajectory.

verify_swpm.py
--------------

Machine-independent functional checks, to be run after any refactor of the
SWPM code (the gold logs above pin one trajectory on one machine; this
script asserts the algorithm's invariants for every reduction scheme and
grouping strategy, determinism, and the documented error conditions):

  python3 verify_swpm.py /path/to/spa_binary
  python3 verify_swpm.py "mpirun -np 4 /path/to/spa_binary"

bkw_init.py
-----------

Generates a Bobylev-Krook-Wu distributed particle set for in.swpm.bkw:

  python3 bkw_init.py 20000 1.0e-6 1.0e-6 1.0e-6 bkw.particles 0.65 273.15 6.63e-26
  spa_<machine> -in in.swpm.bkw

The BKW distribution is an exact solution of the homogeneous Boltzmann
equation for Maxwell molecules: the temperature must stay constant while the
Sonine/higher moments decay to their Maxwellian values.
